# Rule 08 — Vue Template & Component Type Strictness

## Why This Rule Exists

The Vue compiler processes `<template>` HTML blocks through its own AST parser **before** TypeScript sees them. TypeScript constructs inside the template are either silently ignored, produce runtime `undefined`, or crash the compiler. All type narrowing MUST happen in `<script setup>` before the template consumes a value.

---

## 1. Absolute Ban: TypeScript in `<template>`

### ❌ FORBIDDEN — TypeScript casting in template

```vue
<template>
  <!-- FORBIDDEN: 'as Type' assertion -->
  <UserAvatar :user="item as UserInfo" />

  <!-- FORBIDDEN: angle-bracket generic cast -->
  <span>{{ (<string>value).toUpperCase() }}</span>

  <!-- FORBIDDEN: typeof operator -->
  <div v-if="typeof count === 'number'">{{ count }}</div>

  <!-- FORBIDDEN: satisfies operator -->
  <MyComponent :config="opts satisfies Config" />

  <!-- FORBIDDEN: non-null assertion -->
  <span>{{ user!.name }}</span>
</template>
```

All of the above will either silently break, produce a compile error, or cause unexpected runtime behavior.

### ✅ REQUIRED — Narrow types in `<script setup>` via computed

```vue
<script setup lang="ts">
import type { UserInfo } from '@/types/UserTypes'

// Cast once, safely, in script — template receives a clean typed value
const typedUser = computed(() => props.item as UserInfo)
const upperValue = computed(() => (value.value as string).toUpperCase())
const isNumber = computed(() => typeof count.value === 'number')
const userName = computed(() => user.value?.name ?? '')
</script>

<template>
  <UserAvatar :user="typedUser" />
  <span>{{ upperValue }}</span>
  <div v-if="isNumber">{{ count }}</div>
  <span>{{ userName }}</span>
</template>
```

---

## 2. Template Expressions — Allowed vs Forbidden Quick Reference

| Expression type | Template allowed? | Correct location |
|----------------|:-----------------:|-----------------|
| `as Type` cast | ❌ Never | `computed()` in `<script setup>` |
| `typeof x` | ❌ Never | `computed()` in `<script setup>` |
| `x!` non-null assertion | ❌ Never | `computed()` or `x?.y ?? default` |
| `<Type>x` angle-bracket cast | ❌ Never | `computed()` in `<script setup>` |
| `x satisfies T` | ❌ Never | `computed()` in `<script setup>` |
| Ternary `? :` | ✅ Allowed | Template fine for simple conditions |
| Optional chain `?.` | ✅ Allowed | Template safe |
| Nullish coalescing `??` | ✅ Allowed | Template safe |
| Method calls `.toUpperCase()` | ✅ Allowed | Safe when value is already correctly typed |

---

## 3. Absolute Ban: `any` in Component Logic

`any` destroys type safety silently — errors surface only at runtime, never at compile time.

### ❌ FORBIDDEN

```typescript
const data = ref<any>(null)
const items = ref<any[]>([])
function process(val: any): any { /* ... */ }
const handler = (e: any) => e.target.value
```

### ✅ REQUIRED — Explicit types or generics

```typescript
const data = ref<UserInfo | null>(null)
const items = ref<UserInfo[]>([])
function process(val: UserInfo): ProcessedResult { /* ... */ }
const handler = (e: Event) => (e.target as HTMLInputElement).value
```

**`any` is permitted ONLY in these paths (per project governance):**

- `src/adapters/**`
- `src/utils/http/interceptors.ts`
- `src/utils/safeStorage/**`
- `src/utils/date/**`
- `src/components/UseEcharts/**`
- `src/hooks/modules/useChartTheme/**`

---

## 4. `unknown` Requires a Type Guard Before Use

`unknown` is the correct type for external/untyped data, but must be narrowed before accessing any properties or methods.

### ❌ FORBIDDEN

```typescript
function handle(val: unknown) {
  return val.toString() // TS error — unknown has no methods
}
```

### ✅ REQUIRED — Guard before access

```typescript
function handle(val: unknown): string {
  if (typeof val === 'string') return val.toUpperCase()
  if (typeof val === 'number') return String(val)
  return ''
}
```

---

## 5. All Props Must Be Typed

### ❌ FORBIDDEN — untyped runtime array syntax

```typescript
const props = defineProps(['name', 'value'])
```

### ✅ REQUIRED — generic type syntax

```typescript
const props = defineProps<{
  name: string
  value: number
  optional?: boolean
}>()
```

---

## 6. Composables Must Declare Explicit Return Types

Without an explicit return type, TypeScript infers a complex anonymous object type that consumers cannot reference — causing "inferred type cannot be named" build failures in `.d.ts` generation.

### ❌ FORBIDDEN

```typescript
export function useMyFeature() {
  const count = ref(0)
  return { count } // return type inferred — will fail in declaration emit
}
```

### ✅ REQUIRED

```typescript
import type { Ref } from 'vue'

interface MyFeatureReturn {
  count: Ref<number>
  increment: () => void
}

export function useMyFeature(): MyFeatureReturn {
  const count = ref(0)
  const increment = () => count.value++
  return { count, increment }
}
```
